      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) below 5% for hemolysis index QoI across three mesh refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with element counts of 2.1M, 5.8M, and 14.2M cells. GCI for the normalized index of hemolysis was 3.7%, satisfying the acceptance criterion. The medium mesh (5.8M) was selected for production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions replicate the CFD boundary conditions within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench test data were collected at flow rates of 2.5, 4.0, and 6.0 L/min and rotational speeds of 2000 and 2500 RPM, matching CFD inlet/outlet boundary conditions within ±3% of set-point values. Temperature and fluid properties were matched to bovine blood surrogate specifications."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis agrees with experimental values within 15% across all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD predictions of the normalized index of hemolysis were within 9.4% of experimental measurements across all 5 operating points, exceeding the acceptance criterion. Systematic over-prediction at high flow rates is consistent with known turbulence model limitations and does not affect the rank-ordering of operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index) is directly linked to the clinical decision criterion.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the regulatory acceptance metric specified in the 510(k) submission framework for CPB devices. The CFD QoI is identical to the test QoI, ensuring direct comparability without intermediate transformation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
